(49, 48, 60, 'Advanced Medication Awareness Training Course', '<p>This Advanced Medication Awareness course is designed for team leaders, seniors or experienced carer workers whose role involves assisting with or administering medication. The course focuses on the importance of recording and reporting the administration of medicines and also covers other ways to reduce errors/incidents from occurring. Participants will learn about different types of medication and how they are administered and disposed of correctly. This course ensures participants are fully prepared to support patients by administering medication safely and accurately.</p><h4>Programme Overview</h4><ul><li>Establishing roles and responsibilities.</li><li>How to administer medicines, explained?</li><li>MAR charts.</li><li>Disposal of medication.</li><li>Errors.</li><li>Causes and effects.</li></ul><h4>Assessment</h4><ul><li>Approx 3 hours and delegates</li><li>Involves group activities group activities.</li><li>Guided by Trainers</li><li>Full certificate awarded on completion</li></ul>', 3, 700, '2', NULL, NULL),
(50, 48, 60, 'Advanced Nutrition, Healthier Foods and Special Diets Training', '<p>Designed for those working in fields such as fitness, education, catering or healthcare, which are looking to enhance their knowledge of nutrition, healthy foods and special diets.  Participants will be trained regarding the importance of good nutrition and how it can prevent diet-related illness/s. They will also be informed about balanced meals, allergies and intolerance so that they are able to advise others on how to change their diet for the better. </p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4><ul><li>	The importance of a healthy, balanced diet.</li><li>	The effect of diet and nutrients on the body.</li><li>	Factors which affect the nutritional value of food.</li><li>	Diet-related illnesses and how a healthy diet helps to prevent them.</li><li>	Understanding of why different people need different diets.</li><li>	Connection between diet and lifestyle.</li><li>	Allergies and intolerance.</li><li>	Planning meals and menus.</li><li>	Promoting a healthy diet and lifestyle to others.</li><li>	Food and nutrition terminology.</li><li>	Why products need to display accurate nutritional information.</li><li>	Negative impacts of eating processed and manufactured foods.</li><li>	Complying with relevant legislation.</li></ul><h4>Assessment</h4><ul><li>	4 hours. Our experienced trainers will be on</li><li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li><li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li></ul>', 4, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(51, 48, 60, 'Care Certificate; In-house Training', '<p>The ‘Care Certificate’ provides skills for health care and social care workers.  Whilst it is not mandatory, it is expected new members of staff entering the care sector achieve the competency underlined in the Care Certificate. The duration will vary depending on each participant’s circumstances and requirements.</p>                                                                                 <p>It takes, on average, 12 weeks to complete the ‘Care Certificate’.  We will cover the 15 care standards underlined by Health Education England and Skills for Care, and are a replacement for the Common Induction Standards and National Minimum Training Standards. The ‘Care Certificate’ was created as a set of guidelines that supports and protects patients, care workers, care providers and any other staff, by developing the skills needed to work in the health social care sector, the care certificate ensures that the worker is adequately trained to provide the best care to their patients.</p>  <p>We are now offering an all-in-one in-house training week in which each of the 15 standards of care are covered in detail so that staff are best prepared to complete their assessment. In this week, the 15 Standards enshrined in the Care Certificate are covered over a period of 5 days, with a recap and assessment completed on the fifth day.  This course provides care professionals with high quality course material for the delivery of quality care and support in the healthcare sector.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Understanding Your Role</li> <li>	Your Personal Development</li> <li>	Duty of Care</li> <li>	Equality and Diversity</li> <li>	Person Centred Care</li> <li>	Communication</li> <li>	Privacy and Dignity</li> <li>	Fluids and Nutrition</li> <li>	Awareness of Mental Health, Dementia and Learning Disability</li> <li>	Safeguarding Adults</li> <li>	Safeguarding Children</li> <li>	Basic Life Support</li> <li>	Health and Safety</li> <li>	Handling Information</li> <li>	Infection Prevention and Control</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	Participants will be expected to engage in a number of group activities</li>  <li>	Expected work through targeted criteria </li> <li>	Meet the suggested requirements of the CQC care certificate standard.</li>  <li>	Guided Trainer help throughout</li> </ul>', 0, 0, '2', NULL, NULL),
(52, 48, 60, 'Care Planning Awareness Course', '<p>This training course is aimed at anyone working in the care sector and ensures that staff understand the importance of care planning by competently implementing and reviewing care plans.  The course will provide an enhanced understanding of how they, staff, can work effectively alongside other professionals, by sharing best practice, by teaching them how to make initial assessments that meet the needs of each patient.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	How do individual care plans differ?</li> <li>	Why should care plans be updated?</li> <li>	How should we work with other professionals?</li> <li>	Observation skills.</li> <li>	What are the stages of care planning?</li> <li>	How care plans are assessed?</li> <li>	How to create a care plan.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	Takes around 2 hours</li>  <li>	Will be expected to engage in group activities.</li>  <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 2, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(53, 48, 60, 'Communication and Record Keeping', '<p>Provides awareness by highlighting the principles of good communication and record keeping within a care environment, ensuring effective communication skills, and good practices are followed, shared and recorded.  Also provides a clear and accurate audit trail.  - This training is aimed at staff working in a range of care settings and ensures that they leave with enhanced awareness of the principles of good communication and record keeping within their own care environment. Participants will also benefit from improved communication skills which will prove invaluable in delivering good, quality care and maintaining healthy working relationships.</p>  <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> </li>	What is communication?</li> <li>	Effective methods of communication.</li> <li>	Models of communication.</li> <li>	Communication techniques.</li> <li>	The management of communication.</li> <li>	Legislation and best practice.</li> <li>	Effective record keeping.</li> <li>	Keeping records in a care environment.</li> <li>	Preventing errors.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	4 hours.</li>  <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 4, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(54, 48, 60, 'Choking Prevention Awareness Training Course', '<p>Ideal for staff working in care settings, this training teaches Participants about the causes of choking, including the signs and symptoms, and the active steps which can be taken in order to prevent occurrences. Participants will also gain an understanding of different diet options, the foods which could pose a risk to patients, and the practical skills required to assist someone with their eating.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Dysphagia.</li> <li>	Signs and symptoms of choking.</li> <li>	Signs and symptoms of aspiration.</li> <li>	Diet.</li> <li>	Which foods put service users at risk?</li> <li>	Assisting someone with their eating - what to do, and what not to do.</li> <li>	Managing an emergency.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	2 hours</li> <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion</li> </ul>', 2, 275, '2', NULL, NULL),
(55, 48, 60, 'Dementia Awareness Training Course', '<p>Aimed at all staff within the care environment working with older people with dementia. It also provides a general understanding of the issues associated with dementia. Participants will gain under-pinning knowledge in order to recognise the signs and symptoms of dementia; it further focuses on spotting early indicators, the three stages of dementia and diagnosis/treatment of dementia.  This course is designed for any staff working with dementia sufferers in a health or social care setting. It covers the umbrella syndrome that includes associated conditions such as alzheimer\'s disease. Delegates should come away from the session understanding what dementia is, how to manage it and with a greater awareness of the sensitive issues faced by these individuals and their families. This course can be used as an introduction for staff new to the area or as an excellent refresher for those seeking to maintain or update their knowledge.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	What is dementia?</li> <li>	Different kinds of dementia.</li> <li>	How to assist people with dementia and their carers.</li> <li>	Supporting individuals with dementia.</li> <li>	Communication.</li> <li>	Managing behavioural shifts.</li> <li>	Enabling and empowering individuals with dementia.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	3 hours.</li> <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 3, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(56, 48, 60, 'Equality and Diversity Awareness Training Course', '<p>Participants gain awareness of discriminatory practice/s gaining knowledge and practical examples of how best to promote equal opportunities for all, recognising the value of diversity in todays and our future society. Ideal for staff in any sector, this course provides Participants with an understanding of how the values, opinions and prejudices of an individual can influence those around them, and how this can lead to discrimination. Delegates will gain awareness of the value of equality and diversity, and will be encouraged to promote equal opportunities in the workplace.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction.</li> <li>	What is equality and diversity?</li> <li>	Why is equality and diversity important?</li> <li>	Understanding the needs of individuals.</li> <li>	Respecting others and their needs.</li> <li>	Laws and legislations.</li> <li>	Important factors to ensure equality and diversity.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	2 hours.</li> <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 2, 275, '2', NULL, NULL),
(57, 48, 60, 'Falls Prevention Training Course', '<p>An increasing number of people in the UK suffer serious injuries from falls every year. The course ensures that participants are aware of the causes of falls to determine when a person is at risk. Participants will also learn about the effects of falls, both physical and psychological, as well as ways that they can help those who have fallen. Fall prevention training is ideal for staff working in the care sector, especially those working primarily with the elderly.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction.</li> <li>	Personal and environmental risk factors contributing to falls.</li> <li>	Poor vision causing falls – cataract and age-related macular degeneration.</li> <li>	Social, psychological and other implications of falls.</li> <li>	Determining when a person is at risk.</li> <li>	Helping those who have fallen – medical, exercise, awareness, etc.</li> <li>	Injuries caused by falling.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	3 hours.  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 2, 0, '2', NULL, NULL),
(58, 48, 60, 'Incontinence Awareness Training Course', '<p>This training is designed for staff in a range of care settings and ensures an understanding of what incontinence is and the impact it can have on the affected individual. Participants will also be taught the causes of different types of incontinence and effective ways to manage. This training is interactive and delegates will be given the opportunity to shape the way it is delivered by discussing own roles and experiences of managing individuals affected by incontinence. Designed for staff in a range of care settings and ensures an understanding of what incontinence is and the impact it can have on the affected individual. As well as this, participants will be taught about the causes of different types of incontinence and effective ways to manage it. This training is interactive and delegates will be given the opportunity to shape the way it is delivered by discussing their own roles and experiences of managing individuals affected by incontinence.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	What does incontinence mean?</li> <li>	Common causes of incontinence.</li> <li>	Understanding different types of incontinence.</li> <li>	Identifying the assistance available when managing incontinence.</li> <li>	Risks associated with male and female sufferers.</li> <li>	Medicines and treatment.</li> <li>	Complications.</li> <li>	Developing management plans.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <p>The incontinence awareness training course takes around 2 hours and delegates may be expected to engage in a number of group activities. Our experienced trainers will be on hand to help guide participants through these sessions and a certificate will be awarded upon completion</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	What does incontinence mean?</li> <li>	Common causes of incontinence.</li> <li>	Understanding different types of incontinence.</li> <li>	Identifying the assistance available when managing incontinence</li>. <li>	Risks associated with male and female sufferers.</li> <li>	Medicines and treatment.</li> <li>	Complications.</li> <li>	Developing management plans.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	2 hours.  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion </ul>', 2, 275, '2', NULL, NULL),
(59, 48, 60, 'Medication Awareness Training Course', '<p>All participants/workers in the care environment need to work in accordance to the National Minimum Standard Requirements and the CQC guidelines. The learner will have an understanding of the legislation involved with drug administration as well as being able to follow procedures for safe administration.  All participants will also have an understanding of the importance of confidentiality and security in all procedures of drug administration - Medication Awareness is designed to suit a range of care settings and fully complies with the National Minimum Standards, whilst fulfilling CQC guidelines. Upon completion of the course, delegates will be up to date with current legislation whilst also holding a practical understanding of the procedures they must follow in order to ensure that medication is administered safely. The training covers the importance of, and practical issues associated with, confidentiality and information security in drug administration.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction to medication.</li> <li>	Storing and dispensing medicine.</li> <li>	Documentation, confidentiality and record keeping.</li> <li>	Administering medication.</li> <li>	Reducing and eliminating errors in administering medication.</li> <li>	Who is accountable and responsible?</li> <li>	Current legislation and legal requirements.</li> <li>	Regulatory bodies.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	3 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 3, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(60, 48, 60, 'Meaning of CQC Awareness Training Course', '<p>This course provides delegates with an understanding of what the role of the Care Quality Commission is and how the standards they demand affect the care sector. Training is designed for anyone striving to meet the legal requirements and industry standards expected from health care environments and those who work within them.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	About the role of the CQC in the care sector.</li> <li>	Aims of the CQC to ensure quality care.</li> <li>	Inspections that take place.</li> <li>	Meeting standards and requirements.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	2 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 2, 275, '2', NULL, NULL),
(61, 48, 60, 'Mental Capacity Act and Deprivation of Liberties Course for Mangers', '<p>Provides participants with a clear understanding of their responsibilities regarding Deprivation of Liberties Safeguards (DOLS) and the process of following up lawful deprivation. Training will also cover the Mental Capacity Act (MCA) and how it’s implemented throughout the care sector.</p>  <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	Knowledge of relevant legislation.</li> <li>	Gain awareness of MCA and DOLS.</li> <li>	Lawful and unlawful deprivation.</li> <li>	Awareness of Best Interest Decisions.</li> <li>	Understand how the MCA and DOLS impact, and provide support for, those with learning disabilities and mental health conditions.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	6 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 6, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(62, 48, 60, 'Moving and Handling of People Training Course – (Practical)', '<p>Designed to provide participants with the essential knowledge and understanding of the safe process and practices of moving people to prevent injury to themselves and the person needing to be moved, whilst also covering the legal requirements regarding the handling of people. Correct moving and handling of people techniques can save carers from back problems later in life! This course ensures your carers are protecting themselves, and correctly assisting their patients to give them the best support possible.</p> <p>Participants will come away from the training with an array of essential practical skills as well as an understanding of the relevant principles, policies and legal requirements with which they must comply.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Health and Safety at Work (1974).</li> <li>	Manual Handling Regulations (1999).</li> <li>	Duty of care.</li> <li>	Moving and handling assessments.</li> <li>	The principles of safer handling.</li> <li>	Company policies on handling people.</li> <li>	The human anatomy.</li> <li>	Poor and unsafe practice.</li> <li>	Practical assessment.</li> <li>	Using equipment for moving people.</li> <li>	The movement and transfer of people.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	2 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 2, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(63, 48, 60, 'Moving and Handling of People Training Course – (Theory)', '<p>Delivering theory before practical - training helps to ‘set the scene’ and gives delegates an understanding of moving and handling concepts, rather than just the practical aspects. This can dramatically improve the quality of safe handling practices which therefore promotes the best interests of the services recipients. Great introduction for participants who are looking to progress onto the practical course, it also provides essential knowledge for those who are not directly involved in the physical aspects of moving and handling people.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	Relevant legislation associated with safe moving and handling.</li> <li>	How injury affects people differently.</li> <li>	Preventing injuries.</li> <li>	Knowledge of basic anatomy - spine, discs, ligaments, muscles, etc.</li> <li>	Ergonomics and movements.</li> <li>	Bearing the bulk of a person\'s weight.</li> <li>	Safe handling principles and correct handling position.</li> <li>	Appropriate handling techniques in relation to the working environment.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	2 hours.</li> <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 2, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(64, 48, 60, 'Diet and Nutrition Awareness Training Course', '<p>Provides all staff with an introduction in enabling clients to choose and consume food and drink. The actual support required by clients will be dependent on their individual needs. - Training is designed to enable care staff in a range of settings to assist their clients in choosing and orally consuming their food and drink. Participants should leave the course with a clear understanding of how to assess the specific needs of each patient, including the key minerals and nutrients which they may require.  Participants will learn ways in which to vary their patients\' diet in order to help prevent illness as well as the effects which good and bad nutrition can have on their body and health. This course also covers malnutrition and the impact malnutrition has on the body and mind.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	What is nutrition?</li> <li>	Nutrients.</li> <li>	Fruits and vegetables.</li> <li>	Nourishing the elderly.</li> <li>	What is malnutrition and how does it affect the body?</li> <li>	What causes malnutrition?</li> <li>	Screening tools.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	2 hours. </li> <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	Certificate awarded upon successful completion</li> </ul>', 2, 275, '2', NULL, NULL),
(65, 48, 60, 'Nutrition and Malnutrition Universal Screening Tool Course M.U.S.T', '<p>This course provides participants with an understanding of the Malnutrition Universal Screening Tool (M.U.S.T.), a five-step screening tool used in hospitals and care homes to identify adults who are malnourished or at risk of malnutrition or obesity. Training will also cover all general aspects of health and nutrition, making this course ideal not only for those working in the care sector, but also for school cooks and catering assistants.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	Identifying different food groups and their effects.</li> <li>	Energy requirements.</li> <li>	Vitamins and minerals.</li> <li>	Understanding food labels.</li> <li>	Balance diet for good health.</li> <li>	Knowledge of management guidelines which can be used to develop a care plan.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <p>The nutrition and M.U.S.T. awareness course runs over 6 hours and delegates will be expected to engage in a number of group activities. Our experienced trainers will be on hand to help guide delegates through these sessions and a certificate will be awarded upon completion.</p>', 6, 275, '2', NULL, NULL),
(66, 48, 60, '•	Observation Skills for Carers Training Course', '<p>Designed to provide an introduction into the responsibilities in observation and the legal requirements of accurate reporting.  Relevant to all who provide personal care to clients in care settings.  This training is aimed at care staff in a range of settings and ensures that they fulfil their duty of candour as well as their responsibility to accurately report any concerns which they may have, a legal requirement for all care agencies. Participants will also learn how to use different types of records and reports and the reasons why these are required. They will be expected to demonstrate that they can draft written records that are clear, legible and of use to other care professionals.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	What is an observation?</li> <li>	The importance of observations.</li> <li>	Practical observation skills.</li> <li>	Analysis of behaviour.</li> <li>	Developing and maintaining patterns.</li> <li>	Keeping records and reporting concerns.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	2 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 2, 275, '2', NULL, NULL),
(67, 48, 60, 'Managing Challenging Behaviour Training Course', ' <p>This course is designed for care sector staff, although it is also ideal for anyone who may come into contact with people who display traits of challenging behaviour. Training will ensure that delegates are aware of the different types of challenging behaviour and are equipped to manage each situation appropriately. They will understand the impacts which can be caused by challenging behaviour and will be prepared to deal with such outcomes.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	Identifying types of challenging behaviour.</li> <li>	Causes of challenging behaviour/behavioural changes.</li> <li>	The impacts, results and outcomes of challenging behaviour.</li> <li>	How to asses behaviour.</li> <li>	Dealing with the outcomes.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	3 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 3, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(68, 48, 60, 'Person Centred Panning Training Course', '<p>In the government Putting People First policy, it was determined that person centred planning should become the norm. This training course is aimed at staff in the care sector and will teach them the correct procedure to follow when creating personal care plans for patients in regards to this policy. Staff will learn to adapt their care plans to suit the individual needs of each patient, ensuring that they incorporate ideas from other professionals as well as the patients and their families.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction.</li> <li>	What should be included in a plan?</li> <li>	Communicating with the patient.</li> <li>	Supporting the patient.</li> <li>	Successful planning methods.</li> <li>	Incorporating ideas from family, professionals and the patient.</li> <li>	Adapting planning for individuals’ needs.</li> <li>	Working with patients’ budgets.</li> <li>	Overcoming problems.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	3 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 3, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(69, 48, 60, 'Personal Care Training Course', '<p>Aimed at those responsible for providing personal care to service users in a range of care settings. Participants will leave the course with the ability to deliver quality personal care and a clear understanding of the key principles to good care planning. Participants will also be taught the safety rules and industry standard precautions they need to follow in order to protect themselves and the organisation in which they work against any legal implications.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Providing baths and showers for the individual service user.</li> <li>	Mouth, denture, hair, foot and nail care.</li> <li>	The safety rules and standard precautions associated with providing care.</li> <li>	Recording and reporting, and why it is important.</li> <li>	Policies and procedures, and why we need to follow them.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	2 hours. </li> <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 2, 275, '2', NULL, NULL),
(70, 48, 60, 'Risk Assessment Training Course', ' <p>Provides useful information on assessing risks to service users and those facilitating their care.  - Course covers the rules and procedures of recording information and will provide participants with a firm understanding of record types, record keeping and confidentiality of information. The use of Social eCare, (an online resource) designed to assist healthcare professionals with a wide range of administrative tasks, will also be covered.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	Relevant legislation under the Data Protection Act.</li> <li>	Types of information and records kept in health and social care.</li> <li>	Recording information – where, how and when?</li> <li>	Importance of inputting information correctly.</li> <li>	Length of record keeping.</li> <li>	Confidentiality and security.</li> <li>	Using eCare.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	5 hours. </li> <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion</li> </ul>', 5, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(71, 48, 60, 'The Ageing Process Training Course', '<p>Aimed at all staff working in the care environment who work with older people.  Participants will also gain under-pinning knowledge of reality awareness. Designed for those working in care sector settings where they encounter older patients on a regular basis. Participants should come away from the course with an enhanced understanding of the ageing process and how it can affect an individual’s body and mind. Training is interactive and participants will be given the opportunity to shape the way it is delivered through discussing their own roles and experiences.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Best practice when working with older people.</li> <li>	How an individual needs change as they age.</li> <li>	What is the ageing process?</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	2 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 2, 275, '2', NULL, NULL),
(72, NULL, 60, 'Childcare Courses', '', 0, 0, '2', NULL, NULL),
(73, 72, 60, 'Child Protection Awareness Training Course', '<p>Aimed at all staff that is responsible for children in either a residential or community setting. Participants will gain an enhanced insight into child protection issues and helps them develop an understanding of the factors associated with safeguarding children. Participants will gain the vital knowledge and skills they need to manage a range of child protection situations, identifying types of abuse and reporting and recording it appropriately.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Defining the client.</li> <li>	Types of abuse.</li> <li>	How to identify when a child is being abused.</li> <li>	Duty of care.</li> <li>	Whistleblowing.</li> <li>	Child protection agencies.</li> <li>	Case studies.</li> <li>	Record keeping and effective reporting.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	2 hours. </li> <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 2, 275, '2', NULL, NULL),
(74, 72, 60, 'Safeguarding Children Training Course', '<p>Aimed at anyone who works, or has contact, with children, young people and/or their families and provides a detailed insight into duty of care and the implementation of safe practice. Training is designed for delegates who are new to this area and ensures a solid introduction to child safeguarding and the issues surrounding it, although it would also serve as an excellent refresher for staff looking to update their existing knowledge.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Legislation, safeguarding laws and guidance.</li> <li>	Recognising child abuse.</li> <li>	Responding to concerns.</li> <li>	Who to contact if you suspect abuse.</li> <li>	Duty of care awareness.</li> <li>	Safe practice and making sure children are safe.</li></li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	3 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul><p>Aimed at anyone who works, or has contact, with children, young people and/or their families and provides a detailed insight into duty of care and the implementation of safe practice. Training is designed for delegates who are new to this area and ensures a solid introduction to child safeguarding and the issues surrounding it, although it would also serve as an excellent refresher for staff looking to update their existing knowledge.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Legislation, safeguarding laws and guidance.</li> <li>	Recognising child abuse.</li> <li>	Responding to concerns.</li> <li>	Who to contact if you suspect abuse.</li> <li>	Duty of care awareness.</li> <li>	Safe practice and making sure children are safe.</li></li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	3 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 3, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(75, 72, 60, 'Managing Challenging Behaviour & Promoting Positivity Training Course', '<p>Course is aimed at those who care for patients who display challenging behaviour and ensures that they are able to identify positive and negative behaviour and understand the factors which contribute to behavioural change. With this newfound knowledge, participants will be able to assess their patients\' behavioural patterns so as to promote a positive attitude and reduce the effects of challenging behaviour.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	Identifying types of challenging behaviour.</li> <li>	Factors relating to behavioural changes.</li> <li>	Causes of challenging behaviour.</li> <li>	Covering the impacts of challenging behaviour, the results and outcomes.</li> <li>	How to assess behaviour.</li> <li>	Methods to help reduce the impact and promote positive behaviour.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	4 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 4, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(76, 72, 60, 'Attachment and Child Development Training Course', '<p>This course is designed for foster carers as well as anyone interested in child development. Those attending will be equipped with an understanding of a child’s developmental needs as well as insight into attachment theory. The course will also ensure that delegates are able to identify the signs of attachment and understand the subsequent impact on a child\'s behaviour.</p> <h4>Programme Overview<h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	Identifying children’s developmental needs and providing appropriate support.</li> <li>	Recognising that each child is different.</li> <li>	Understanding the notion of patterns involved with attachment</li> <li>	The relationship between parenting and attachment patterns.</li> <li>	Linking attachment patterns to a child’s behaviour.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	4 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 4, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(77, 72, 60, 'Caring for Children who have been Abused Training Course', '<p>Ideal for anyone working predominantly with children, including teachers, police, social workers, GPs and youth workers. Participants will be aware of the different types of abuse and the effects which they cause. Participants will also learn how to identify signs of abuse and provide those children affected with the support and communication they need by building a trusting relationship based on trust, ensuring that no further abuse occurs.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Identifying the signs of abuse in children.</li> <li>	Categories of abuse; sexual, emotional, domestic, Honour Based Violence (HBV) and neglect.</li> <li>	Results of abuse such as self-harm, violence and suicide.</li> <li>	Trust and communication with abused children.</li> <li>	Legal responsibility – reporting the abuse.</li> <li>	Mental and physical recovery.</li> <li>	Safeguarding children against further abuse.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	6 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 6, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(78, 72, 60, 'Attachment Awareness Training Course', '<p>Designed for those with no current knowledge of attachment theory, serving further as a great resource for anyone looking to further their understanding of the subject. Covers everything from the basic nature of attachment and the causes, through to dealing with its impacts and the behavioural effects.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	The nature of attachment and how it forms.</li> <li>	Identify and understand different types of attachment.</li> <li>	Knowledge of a child’s early neurological development.</li> <li>	Maximising the security of the child through parenting behaviours.</li> <li>	How attachment can be distorted by parental/carer behaviour.</li> <li>	Understanding the effects of separation and loss on children.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	4 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 4, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(79, 72, 60, 'Attachment Awareness Training Course', '<p>This course is aimed towards foster carers and those working in the childcare sector. Delegates will gain an understanding of typical behavioural and emotional patterns which children display at different developmental ages, so that they can assess whether a child who has experienced separation or loss is developing as expected. Training will also teach delegates how to care for, and build trust with, children who have experienced separation or loss, whilst helping them to deal with the grief.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul>	 <li>	Introduction.</li> <li>	The stages of separation and loss.</li> <li>	Behaviour and emotions through developmental ages.</li> <li>	Triggers – smells, sounds, stress, etc.</li> <li>	Supporting a child as they deal with their loss or separation.</li> <li>	Building trust between you and a child.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	4 hours</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 4, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(80, 72, 60, 'Children and the Youth Justice', '<p>This course is designed for social workers who are working, or looking to work, within the youth justice system and who intend to assist in preventing young people from re-offending. This training ensures that delegates are aware of the Youth Justice System processes and procedures, and are able to work safely with children who may be of risk. This is the ideal course to take subsequent to our Youth Crime and Anti-Social Behaviour course.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	Full understanding of all current legislation.</li> <li>	Carrying out risk assessments.</li> <li>	Multi-agency working.</li> <li>	How to work with high risk children appropriately.</li> <li>	Covering different types of interventions.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	4hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 4, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(81, 72, 60, 'Child Sexual Exploitation Awareness Training Course', '<p>Designed for staff, such as social workers, whose main working role is to ensure the safeguarding of children. Training will provide delegates with strong foundation knowledge of the issues of child sexual exploitation (CSE) as well as ensuring that they develop the ability to identify the signs, indicators, and motivators of exploitation. They will also be given an insight into the impact of CSE and what to do if they have concerns about a child.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	What is meant by the term ‘child sexual exploitation’?</li> <li>	Awareness of national guidance, law and frameworks relating to CSE.</li> <li>	Understand why every child and young person is vulnerable.</li> <li>	Responding to concerns, assessing risk and sharing information.</li> <li>	Knowledge of how young people become involved, the grooming process, the impact of the abuse and how young people often respond.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	4 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 4, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(82, 72, 60, 'Working with Unaccompanied Minors Training Course', '<p>Provides participants with an overview of the relevant legal policies and procedures involved when working with unaccompanied minors. Delegates will gain understanding of the common issues faced by these children and will be able to provide appropriate care and support. Training will relate back to the day-to-day experiences of the delegates, and is therefore ideal for care and social workers.</p> <h4>Outline of Programme</h4> <ul> <li>	Understanding of who unaccompanied minors are.</li> <li>	The roles of different adults in the system.</li> <li>	Knowledge of the legal policy framework for support and care.</li> <li>	The impact of the asylum process on care planning.</li> <li>	The common issues faced by unaccompanied minors and those working with them.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	5hours. </li> <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 5, 375, '2', NULL, NULL),
(83, 72, 60, 'Working with Minors who display Sexually Harmful Behaviour Training Course', '<p>Designed for those, such as social workers and foster carers, who work with children and young people displaying sexually harmful behaviour. Training provides delegates with an array of theoretical knowledge, from understanding safeguarding issues to identifying sexualised behaviour and effectively providing support. Participants will also become equipped with the practical training required to deal with potential situations confidently.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	How to identify sexualised behaviour.</li> <li>	Understanding of safeguarding issues.</li> <li>	Motivations behind actions.</li> <li>	Responsibilities when dealing with situations.</li> <li>	Knowledge of self-harm and risk taking.</li> <li>	Difficulties of protecting those vulnerable to exploitation over the internet.</li> <li>	Apply approaches appropriately to help those who display sexually harmful or sexualised behaviour.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	6 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 6, 375, '2', NULL, NULL),
(84, 72, 60, 'Working with Children who display sexually harmful/aggressive behaviour', '<p>Designed for those, such as social workers and foster carers, who work with children and young people displaying sexually harmful behaviour. Training provides delegates with an array of theoretical knowledge, from understanding safeguarding issues to identifying sexualised behaviour and providing support. As well as this, delegates will become equipped with the practical training required to deal with potential situations confidently.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	How to identify sexualised behaviour.</li> <li>	Understanding of safeguarding issues.</li> <li>	Motivations behind actions.</li> <li>	Responsibilities when dealing with situations.</li> <li>	Knowledge of self-harm and risk taking.</li> <li>	Difficulties of protecting those vulnerable to exploitation over the internet.</li> <li>	Apply approaches appropriately to help those who display sexually harmful or sexualised behaviour.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	6 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 6, 375, '2', NULL, NULL),
(85, 72, 60, 'Working with Sexualised Behaviours Awareness Training Course', '<p> With the media and the introduction of the internet exposing and promoting sexual behaviour to our children it is no wonder these unfortunate incidents are on the rise.  Ideal for those working primarily with children and looking to address any potentially inappropriate behaviour, delegates will gain an understanding of legal guidelines and the meaning of consent and competency. Training will also ensure that participants are able to identify sexualised behaviour and support those who have been affected by it.</p>   <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction.</li> <li>	Consent and competency.</li> <li>	Gillick competence and Fraser guidelines.</li> <li>	Harmful sexual behaviour.</li> <li>	Signs and symptoms.</li> <li>	Sexual behaviour continuum.</li> <li>	Causes and effects of sexualised behaviour.</li> <li>	Supporting those affected.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	3hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 3, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(86, 72, 60, 'Dealing with Sexually Abused Young People Training Course', '<p>Aimed at staff whose role primarily involves working with children; this includes police, social workers, carers and GPs. Training will ensure that delegates are aware of the signs and effects of abuse so that they are able to identify when it has occurred and then provide children with the support they need. Participants will also be advised on ways in which they can communicate and build trust with abused children so as to help them to recover both physically and mentally.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	Legal responsibilities.</li> <li>	How to identify signs of sexual abuse.</li> <li>	Common effects abuse has on a child.</li> <li>	Building trust and communication with an abused child.</li> <li>	Mental and physical recovery.</li> <li>	Prevention of further abuse.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	4 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 4, 345, '2', NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `categories_backup2` (`id`, `sub_category_id`, `disciplines_id`, `name`, `course_detail`, `duration`, `cost`, `status`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(87, 72, 60, 'Parent and Child Placement Training Course', '<p>Introduces and explores the use of parent and child placements within foster care and the roles and responsibilities of both foster carers and parents. Training will enable practitioners to make safe and suitable placement choices in response to identifying each child’s individual needs and their parent’s capabilities to meet them.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	Understanding the legal requirements in relation to parent and child placements.</li> <li>	Identify and plan for safeguarding issues in these placements.</li> <li>	Understand the roles and responsibilities of the foster carer and the parent.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	4hours. </li> <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition </li>, <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completio.</li> </ul>', 4, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(88, 72, 60, 'Men who Foster Training Course', '<p>Designed to help participants identify the true value of male foster carers and the requirements of such a demanding role. Participants are aware of general attitudes towards men who foster and possible fears which these men may hold. Designed for social workers and those looking to foster and provides insight into ways in which they can improve the quality of life of children and young people within their care.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	Legislation, policy and procedures involved with fostering.</li> <li>	About the role of male foster carers.</li> <li>	Understanding the attitudes towards men who foster.</li> <li>	Discuss possible fears men may have about being a foster carer.</li> <li>	Covering the idea of “male role models”.</li> <li>	The importance of the relationship for children/young people in care.</li> <li>	Exploring the difference between men and women’s roles.</li> <li>	Dealing with any possible allegations.</li> <li>	Ways of gaining ongoing support and advice for carers.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	4 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 4, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(89, 72, 60, 'Preparing Young People for Independence Training Course', '<p>Provides participants with the knowledge and skills needed to assist young people with the transition into independent living. Participants will gain understanding of the issues and challenges which young people face as well as ways in which they can help them to overcome these. This training is suitable for anyone involved with foster care, as well as those who are looking to assist in the process of moving children and young people on.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	Gain knowledge to help young adults to live in the community successfully.</li> <li>	Support young people with the current issues and challenges they face.</li> <li>	Assist young people in developing resilience.</li> <li>	Creating links between young people and other professionals.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	4 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 4, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(90, 72, 60, 'Youth Crime and Anti Social Behaviour Training Course', '<p>Designed to provide social workers and foster carers with the skills required to aid the prevention and reduction of youth crime and anti-social behaviour. Training will provide delegates with a basic overview of current legislation and will ensure that they are able to understand each child’s motivations and experiences.</p>  <p>A deeper insight into the youth justice system is covered on our Children and the Youth Justice System course and we highly recommend speaking to one of our training consultants to find out which course is best suited to your needs.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	Knowledge of current legislation.</li> <li>	Identifying motives.</li> <li>	Understanding the impact a child’s experiences can have on their behaviour.</li> <li>	Recognising that each child is different.</li> <li>	Signs of crime and anti-social behaviour.</li> <li>	Different intervention methods.</li> <li>	Advice and support available.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	4 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 4, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(91, 72, 60, 'Contact and Working with Birth families Training Course', '<p>For children in foster care, maintaining links with their families is hugely important.  Responsibility often falls into the hands of the foster carer and their role is key to ensuring that children are well-prepared and that contact is a positive experience. Foster carers must also support the children should the contact end, therefore, we’ve ensured the course is thorough in order to cover most-if-not-all eventualities.</p>  <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	Aims of contact and legal responsibilities.</li> <li>	Learn how carers can develop skills in relation to contact.</li> <li>	Gain advice, discuss experiences and support others.</li> <li>	Build effective strategies for dealing with contact difficulties.</li> <li>	Addressing contact within an anti-discriminatory framework.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	4 hours. </li> <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 4, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(92, 72, 60, 'Managing Allegations against Foster Carers Training Course', '<p>Participants will be made aware of the correct ways in which to handle allegations and complaints made against foster carers.  We provide an insight into how to understand the complaints and allegations, and provide appropriate support to carers during a dispute. The course is suitable for a wide breadth of people, ranging from fostering service managers, family placement workers, social workers or any other persons involved in this working environment.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul>	 <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	Develop a well-rounded and realistic understanding of allegations and complaints.</li> <li>	How different fostering roles can be used to minimise these allegations.</li> <li>	Examine implications of policy and procedures in relation to DFE guidance.</li> <li>	Explore the support available for carers and their families during a dispute.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	4 hours.</li> <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 4, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(93, 72, 60, 'Signs of Child Trafficking Training Course', '<p>Introduces participants to the subject of child trafficking and ensures that they are equipped with sufficient skills and knowledge to identify indicators that such events have occurred. Participants will learn how to refer affected children to the appropriate services, using legislation to support and protect them against further incidents.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	Gain an understanding of child trafficking and the issues involved.</li> <li>	Learn about trafficking within the context of safeguarding.</li> <li>	How to identify possible indicators that a child may have been trafficked.</li> <li>	Knowledge of how legislation can be used in order to protect children.</li> <li>	Understand how Children’s Services respond to a suspected case of trafficking.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	3 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 3, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(94, 72, 60, 'Fostering Unaccompanied Asylum Seeking and Refugee Children Training Course', '<p>Provides delegates with an understanding of the experiences and circumstances of unaccompanied asylum seeking and refugee children. Along with knowledge of the latest research and legislative standards, the training also ensures that delegates are equipped with the specific skills needed to deliver the supportive care required.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	Understanding of the legal status and position of the children.</li> <li>	Identify their needs and how to meet them.</li> <li>	Understanding the impact of the “refugee-making” and the carer’s role.</li> <li>	Lasting effects that trauma, loss and separation can have on young people.</li> <li>	Learn the specific skills that may be useful when caring for unaccompanied asylum seeking and refugee children.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	4 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 4, 375, '2', NULL, NULL),
(95, 72, 60, 'Supporting Education Potential Training Course', '<p>The education and achievements of children in foster care should be actively valued as an essential part of their preparation for adulthood. By teaching both theory and practical skills, this course ensures that delegates are compliant with the National Minimum Standards (Fostering Standard 8) whilst best preparing them to help young people reach their potential and achieve their educational aspirations.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	Understanding the requirements of the National Minimum Standards.</li> <li>	How to support children in identifying their educational aspirations.</li> <li>	Helping plan and assess educational opportunities and activities.</li> <li>	Reviewing progress of opportunities and activities.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	4 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 4, 375, '2', NULL, NULL),
(96, 72, 60, 'Education and Success in Learning', '<p>It is compulsory for all young people in the UK aged between 4 and 18 to receive some form of education. This course ensures that children and teenagers are fully supported throughout this time so that they are able to achieve their full potential. Training is designed for those caring and/or responsible for a child who is currently in education; this could include teachers, parents and foster carers to name a few. Delegates will understand the factors which affect success and ways in which they can allow learners to reach their full potential.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	What makes a successful learner?</li> <li>	How definitions of success affect children.</li> <li>	Factors affecting success in education.</li> <li>	Understanding each child’s abilities.</li> <li>	Theories and motivations to allow children to reach their academic potential.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	6 hours – 1 day</li> <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 6, 399, '2', NULL, NULL),
(97, NULL, 60, 'Health & Safety', '', 0, 0, '2', NULL, NULL),
(98, 97, 60, 'Physical Intervention Training', '<p>Physical intervention skills are sometimes required for the safe and legal management of physically challenging behaviour. Participants will learn a range of skills which are essential when working with patients who have learning disabilities or mental health problems.</p>  <p>We may be able to offer you a bespoke training package, specifically designed to suit your area of business and focusing on the specific risks and challenges your organisation might face.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction to physical intervention.</li> <li>	Identifying challenging behaviour and knowing when to intervene.</li> <li>	Physical intervention techniques, including breaking away and holding.</li> <li>	Risks involved in physical intervention.</li> <li>	The Assault Cycle.</li> <li>	Laws and legislation.</li> <li>	Triggers of challenging behaviour.</li> <li>	Causes and diffusion of anger and aggression.</li> <li>	Unacceptable practice.</li> <li>	Duty of care.</li> <li>	Threatening behaviour and physical assault.</li> <li>	Dementia and how to intervene physically.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	6  hours - ( 1 day)</li> <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 6, 399, '2', NULL, NULL),
(99, 97, 60, 'Control of Substances Hazardous to Health (COSSH) Awareness Training Course', '<p>The Control of Substances Hazardous to Health (COSHH) Awareness training course will inform participants of the COSHH Regulations (2002) as well as providing them with knowledge of risk assessment and hazards. This course is ideal for those handling hazardous substances daily at work that have no prior knowledge of the subject, or those who wish to refresh their current understanding.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Gain an understanding of COSHH regulations.</li> <li>	Risk assessment and safety procedures.</li> <li>	Definition of hazardous substances.</li> <li>	Compliance with relevant regulations.</li> <li>	Different types of hazardous substances.</li> <li>	Health effects.</li> <li>	European CLP Regulations (replacing Chemicals Hazard Information and Packaging for Supply (CHIP) Regulations as of 01/06/2015).</li> <li>	Workplace injuries and bleeding.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	2 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 2, 275, '2', NULL, NULL),
(100, 97, 60, 'CIEH Hygiene in Health & Social Care Training Course', '<p>The Department of Health has published a code of practice acknowledging that everyone involved in care provision needs training to tackle the risk of Health Care Acquired Infection (HCAI). As such, this new CIEH Health and Safety qualification for Hygiene in Health and Social Care is suitable for all staff working in private, public and voluntary healthcare sectors, providing a useful introduction to hygiene and infection control. Participants will also come away from the course knowing what they can do to ensure that vulnerable individuals are not exposed to avoidable risk, how to maintain infection control and in what way they should contribute to ensuring that their workplace is clean, safe and hygienic.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	What are hygiene hazards?</li> <li>	Personal hygiene best practice.</li> <li>	Cleaning best practice.</li> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	 3 hours.</li>  <li>     Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 3, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(101, 97, 60, 'CIEH/HABC Award in the Principles of COSHH - (Level 2)', '<p>This CIEH level 2 qualification benefits anyone who comes into contact with hazardous substances at work.  Participants will come away from the course with an understanding of different substances, their associated risks, and effective control methods used to manage them. Training will add real value to any organisation seeking to ensure that hazardous substances are managed appropriately on their site. The course also focuses on what a Control of Substances Hazardous to Health (COSHH) assessment would involve.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	What substances might be hazardous to health in the workplace?</li> <li>	The impact hazardous substances can have on health.</li> <li>	COSHH assessments and control options.</li> <li>	Responsibilities under Control of Substances Hazardous to Health Regulations 2002.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	3 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 3, 375, '2', NULL, NULL),
(102, 97, 60, 'Risk Assessment in Care Training Course', '<p>Ensures that participants are aware of the importance of risk assessments in care environments and that they are equipped with the skills and knowledge required to undertake them appropriately for this specific sector.  It further teaches participants the correct procedure to follow when assessing premises and its facilities, making sure they are not only compliant but equally as aware of all relevant laws and legislation which need to be adhered in order to comply. Designed for staff that are responsible for providing health and social care to patients, but nevertheless, it would be beneficial for anyone who requires a general understanding of risk assessments.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction.</li> <li>	Importance of risk assessment.</li> <li>	Correct procedure.</li> <li>	Association with moving and handling of objects.</li> <li>	Assessing premises and its facilities.</li> <li>	Lone worker safety.</li> <li>	Laws and legislation.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment<h4> <ul> <li>	3 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 3, 345, '2', NULL, NULL),
(103, 97, 60, 'Conflict Management & Challenging Behaviour Awareness Course', '<p>Designed for staff in any sector and ensures that they are able to confidently address challenging behaviour in the workplace and also manage conflict to avoid future incidents. Participants will gain a range of skills which will enable them to ensure the safety of themselves and those around them whilst dealing with difficult situations.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction.</li> <li>	Identifying challenging behaviour.</li> <li>	Eliminating violence and bullying in the workplace.</li> <li>	Appropriate response to threats and aggression.</li> <li>	Promoting positivity to reduce conflict.</li> <li>	Conflict management process.</li> <li>	Ensuring personal safety when managing conflicts.</li> <li>	Communication skills (verbal and non-verbal).</li> <li>	Causes and effects.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	2 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 2, 275, '2', NULL, NULL),
