(122, 97, NULL, 'CIEH Conflict Resolution & Personal Safety Training Course (Level 2)', '<p>The CIEH have created the Conflict Resolution and Personal Safety training course to help protect staff against workplace violence. Employers have a duty of care to provide for their staff and any violence can be both physically and psychologically damaging. Over the duration of this course delegates will learn ways of dealing with confrontation so as to maintain a safe working environment.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction to the CIEH and the course.</li> <li>	Laws and legislation.</li> <li>	Creating and maintaining a safe working environment.</li> <li>	De-escalating confrontation.</li> <li>	Ensuring safety of themselves and others.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	3 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 3, 375, '0', NULL, NULL),
(123, 97, NULL, 'Non Violent Crisis Intervention Care Training Course', '<p>This course trains delegates to recognise changes in attitude which could potentially lead to escalating negative behaviour. They will learn to respond promptly and appropriately, using both verbal and non-verbal techniques in order to de-escalate the situation whilst ensuring their own personal safety. With the intention of overcoming any fears which may hold them back, delegates will be asked to address the stresses and anxieties which they have when facing challenging situations and confrontation.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	Quickly identify changes in behaviour that could potentially lead to a crisis.</li> <li>	How to respond appropriately and prevent a situation from escalating.</li> <li>	Use of verbal/non-verbal techniques to defuse a situation.</li> <li>	Dealing with own personal fears, stresses and anxieties</li> <li>	Team and solo intervention.</li> <li>	The safe, non-harmful use of physical restraint as a last resort.</li> <li>	Personal safety in the circumstance of behaviour becoming physical.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	4 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 4, 375, '', NULL, NULL),
(124, 97, NULL, 'Back Safety Awareness Training Course', '<p>Designed to suit staff in any sector and ensures that they gain a better understanding of back pain; both how to deal with it, and how to avoid it. Participants will learn of both the causes and symptoms of back pain so as to prevent it from occurring as well as treatment methods used to minimise and nullify pain.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Causes of back pain, including bad posture, lifting or bending.</li> <li>	Dealing with back pain and speeding up recovery.</li> <li>	Suitable equipment to prevent back pain, including adjustable seats.</li> <li>	Symptoms of back pain.</li> <li>	Types of back pain, including whiplash, slipped disc, etc.</li> <li>	Treatment of back pain when it doesn’t go away, including classes, acupuncture, therapy and spinal surgery if really necessary.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	2 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 Certificate awarded upon successful completion.</li> </ul>', 2, 275, '', NULL, NULL),
(125, 97, NULL, 'Sharps and Needles Awareness', '<p>Designed for those whose working role means that they are at a higher risk of injury from used and discarded needles, syringes or sharps; this includes those who undertake manual handling as part of their working role, as well as staff working for the local authorities. Training will enable delegates to identify report and prevent any risks relating to sharps and needles so as to avoid any incidents, although they will also learn to treat injuries should they occur.</p> <h4>Programme Outline</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	Current legislation.</li> <li>	Identify a sharp and how it can cause injury.</li> <li>	Risks associated with injury.</li> <li>	Treatment of injury.</li> <li>	Reporting injury.</li> <li>	Understanding of blood borne viruses and tetanus.</li> <li>	Where sharps are mostly likely to be found.</li> <li>	Risk assessment.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	3 hours.</li> <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities/discussions</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 A written assessment will be taken on completion.</li> </uL>', 3, 345, '', NULL, NULL),
(126, 97, NULL, 'Evacuation Chair Training', '<p>Designed to teach participants the safe and successful operation of an evacuation chair in response to an emergency situation. The course ensures that organisations are compliant with the Disabled Discrimination Act 2005 and Equality Act 2010. Under these acts it is unlawful to discriminate against any person with regard to any disability, including the evacuation of your premises in the event of a fire.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	How to use an evacuation chair safely under supervision.</li> <li>	Assembling an evacuation chair with confidence.</li> <li>	Understand when an evacuation chair may be required to be used.</li> <li>	Understand the term Fire Refuge Point.</li> <li>	Demonstrate the balance point of an evacuation chair.</li> <li>	Experience the feeling of travelling in an evacuation chair.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	3 hours. </li> <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities/discussions </li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 A certificate will be awarded upon completion.</li> </ul>', 3, 345, '', NULL, NULL),
(127, 97, NULL, 'Evacuation Sledge Training Course', '<p>Under the Disabled Discrimination Act 2005 and Equality Act 2010 it is unlawful to discriminate against any person with regard to any disability they may have. This course teaches delegates how to operate an evacuation sledge safely and successfully in an emergency; this includes the evacuation of your premises in the event of a fire. The course is designed for anyone whose job role includes responsibility for assisting in the evacuation of any person with mobility impairment.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	Understand regulations affecting the mobility impaired.</li> <li>	How to prepare and secure a person to an evacuation sledge safely.</li> <li>	Knowledge of when an evacuation sledge may be required.</li> <li>	Manoeuvring the evacuation sledge up/down stairs.</li> <li>	Restrictions and disadvantages of equipment.</li> <li>	Ability to operate confidently.</li> <li>	Manual handling involved with the equipment and operation.</li> <li>	Understand the term Fire Refuge Point.</li> <li>	Experience the feeling of travelling in an evacuation sledge.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	3 hours. </li> <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities/discussions</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 A certificate will be awarded upon completion.</li> </ul><p>Under the Disabled Discrimination Act 2005 and Equality Act 2010 it is unlawful to discriminate against any person with regard to any disability they may have. This course teaches delegates how to operate an evacuation sledge safely and successfully in an emergency; this includes the evacuation of your premises in the event of a fire. The course is designed for anyone whose job role includes responsibility for assisting in the evacuation of any person with mobility impairment.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction and explanation.</li> <li>	Understand regulations affecting the mobility impaired.</li> <li>	How to prepare and secure a person to an evacuation sledge safely.</li> <li>	Knowledge of when an evacuation sledge may be required.</li> <li>	Manoeuvring the evacuation sledge up/down stairs.</li> <li>	Restrictions and disadvantages of equipment.</li> <li>	Ability to operate confidently.</li> <li>	Manual handling involved with the equipment and operation.</li> <li>	Understand the term Fire Refuge Point.</li> <li>	Experience the feeling of travelling in an evacuation sledge.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	3 hours. </li> <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities/discussions</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 A certificate will be awarded upon completion.</li> </ul>', 3, 345, '', NULL, NULL),
(128, 97, NULL, 'Passenger Safety Awareness Training Course ', '<p>Designed for bus, minibus and coach drivers, as well as others in similar roles, this course provides an understanding of duty of care and legal requirements such as the Road Traffic Act. Delegates will learn how to undertake checks and assessments to ensure that the vehicle is operating safely in addition to knowledge of how to handle emergency situations, should they occur.</p> <h4>Programme Overview</h4> <ul> <li>	Introduction.</li> <li>	Health and safety.</li> <li>	Duty of care.</li> <li>	General safety checks.</li> <li>	Avoiding accidents.</li> <li>	Common causes of injury.</li> <li>	Moving and handling.</li> <li>	Dealing with a fire on board.</li> <li>	Accidents.</li> <li>	Evacuating the vehicle.</li> <li>	Risk assessment.</li> <li>	Dealing with passengers.</li> <li>	Laws and legislations.</li> </ul> <h4>Assessment</h4> <ul> <li>	3 hours.</li>  <li>	Expected to engage in a number of group activities/discussions</li> <li>	 Hands on Guided Tuition</li> <li>	 A certificate will be awarded upon completion.</li> </ul>', 3, 345, '', NULL, NULL),
